<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-Identify-Formulas">
    <title>Identify Formulas to use: Simple, Compound, Annuity, Loan</title>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-finance-answers">
  <title>Identify the Formula to Use</title>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Lonnie needs extra money to buy a truck to start up a delivery service. He
takes out a simple interest loan for $7,000 for 6 months at a rate of 7.25%.
How much interest must he pay, and what is the future value of the loan?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>I = Prt</m>; Interest: $253.75; Future Value: $7,253.75</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>If you placed $1 into an account that paid interest at a rate of 5% and
compounded the interest daily, how much would that account is worth in
300 years?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>A = P(1 + r/n)^{nt}</m>; $3,268,864.51</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>You are purchasing a house for $155,000. The bank requires a down payment of 15% and 2.25 points at closing. The bank will give you a 20 year
mortgage at 3.8%. What is the monthly payment you will make? What is
the total interest paid?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>PMT = \frac{P(r/n)}{1-(1+r/n)^{-nt}}</m>; Monthly Payment: $783.50; Total Interest: $56,289.44</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>You deposit $8,500 for 9 years in an account that earns 2.5% interest and
compounds weekly. How much interest will you earn?</p>    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>A = P(1 + r/n)^{nt}</m>; $2,143.91</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>You lend 650 dollars to your younger brother for tuition. He agrees to pay
you back $720 in 4 months. What is the interest rate he paid you?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>r = \frac{I}{Pt}</m>; 32.31%</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>A mother invests $ 2000 in a bank account at the time of her daughter's
birth. The interest is compounded quarterly at a rate of 8%. What will be
the value of the daughter's account on her twentieth birthday?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>A = P(1 + r/n)^{nt}</m>; $9,750.88</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Your grandmother lent you $2000 for 4 years to buy a car. You agreed to
pay her 5% interest. How much do you have to pay her in total at the end
of 4 years?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>A = P(1 + rt)</m>; $2,400.00</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Which is the better choice: $1000 deposited for a year at a rate of 5.5%
compounded semiannually or at a rate of 5.4% compounded quarterly?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p> <m>APY = (1 + r/n)^n - 1</m>; 5.5% compounded semiannually ($1,055.76 vs $1,055.10)</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Ellen puts $100 each month into an IRA that pays 7.4% annually. How
much money will she have in 30 years for her retirement? How much will
come from interest?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m> A = \frac{PMT[(1+r/n)^{nt}-1]}{r/n}</m>; Total Value: $132,410.87; Interest: $96,410.87</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>You want to save for your three year olds college education. You decide
that you need $200,000 in 12 years. How much do you need to deposit
monthly into an account that pays 8.7% interest and compounds monthly.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>PMT = \frac{A(r/n)}{(1+r/n)^{nt}-1}</m>; $796.86</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Joe and Susan are purchasing a condo for $350,000. The bank requires a
down payment of 30% and 4.75 points at closing. You are considering a 15
year mortgage at 4.75% and a 30 year mortgage at 3.2%. Which mortgage
will result in a lower monthly payment?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>PMT = \frac{P(r/n)}{1-(1+r/n)^{-nt}}</m>;  Option B: 30-year at 3.2% ($1,061.27 vs Option A: $1,906.18)</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Pete wants to buy a boat in 4 years. The boat costs $100,000. How much
money does he need to deposit weekly into an account that pays 3.5%
interest compounded weekly?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>PMT = \frac{A(r/n)}{(1+r/n)^{nt}-1}</m>; $447.93</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>How much money should be deposited today in an account that earns 10%
compounded semiannually so that it will accumulate to $ 1000 in 12 years?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p> <m>P = \frac{A}{(1+r/n)^{nt}}</m>; $310.07</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Juan can save $50 every week for his honeymoon. If Juan is getting married
in two years how much money will he have spent on the trip if he puts it
into an annuity that pays 6%?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>A = \frac{PMT[(1+r/n)^{nt}-1]}{r/n}</m>; $5,516.48</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>How much money should be deposited today in an account that earns 8%
compounded quarterly so that it will accumulate to $ 3800 in 12 years?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>P = \frac{A}{(1+r/n)^{nt}}</m>; $1,468.32</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>
</exercises>

</section>